              <fieldlabel>grading_notes</fieldlabel>
              <fieldentry>The metric of goodness is the ratio of what you want divided by what you pay for. In this case, what you want is the output power, and what you pay for is the input power.</fieldentry>
            </qtimetadatafield>
          </qtimetadata>
        </itemmetadata>
        <presentation>
          <material>
            <mattext texttype="text/html">&lt;p&gt;For this machine the &lt;em&gt;metric of goodness&lt;/em&gt; is the efficiency and was computed by taking the ratio of the output power and by the input power. Why should the metric of goodness for this machine be computed in that way, and not some other way? For example, why would you not compute it by taking the ratio of the output power and the rate of heat radiation, or the ratio of the rate of heat radiation and the input power?&lt;/p&gt;</mattext>
          </material>
